pumps in flight and wind up a different set? Under varying G<br>
forces and vibration loads?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 How about pressure-fed? Back to Truax, eliminate complexity wherever possible. (BTW, tripropellant designs burn <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> both</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> H2/RP with O2, instead of switching over. Hotter, more energetic exhaust than straight RP, higher thrust, with lower bulk fuel than straight H2).<br>
<br>
 Sure, it still requires plumbing &amp; such, but the point is that this may mean less overall mass (and complexity &amp; cost associated with the larger airframe &amp; tankage) than bi-propellant. <br>
 The Sea Dragon used a first stage which fell back slightly downrange. <br>
(hypothetical variant) The first stage carries (CH4 or) kerosene, and burns it with H2/O2 from the upper stage (Extra plumbing to pipe fuels from upper stage tankage to the lower <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> may still be easier</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than extra tankage &amp; airframe on the lower stage. If not,then the first stage just gets that much bigger, and the upper that much smaller).<br>
 The upper stage then burns H2/O2. By this time, it's moving fast (not clear if sub-sonic staging is better than mach-5+ staging), at high altitude.<br>
 Pressurization for the tripropellant fuel in the 1st stage are in that stage. Pressurization for the H2/O2 in the upper stage doesn't turn on/off, rather it stops flowing when hydrocarbon fuel starts to run out in the 1st. Maybe valves in the interstage area turn off flow from the upper tanks. All it requires is ignition of the upper stage after the 1st falls away, and that has to happen anyway with multi-staging.<br>
<br>
 That's the point of tripropellant; it may still be easier &amp; cheaper, because of less tankage &amp; airframe to hold bulkier, less dense fuels, even if it means more plumbing. All I was saying was that it'd be interesting to see the numbers crunched to find out about it.<br>
 For that matter, it might still be cheaper &amp; easier to expend the stages, instead of making them re-usable... Never know until the numbers are thoroughly worked over.<br>
<br>
 I'm a firm believer in bulk dumb lower stages in general. Vastly lower performance requirements if you get it moving. Even strapons, though solids are questionable. Nice thing about parallel burning strapons is that the upper burns continuously, instead of firing off in mid-air, afterletting the lower fall away to a safe distance. Though this doesn't seem to present them with too much trouble in practise.<br>
