<br>
Weather is another thing.<br>
 True, open ocean can get hairy, but not so much at the equators.<br>
Remember that storms get most of their ferocity from coriolis force, which zeros out at the equator. Hurricanes fizzle out rapidly near the equator, and don't form until they get farther N or S. Winds rarely go above 20kts, waves hardly ever above 5' or so.<br>
 Old sailors called the equatorial regions the doldrums, because that's the most likely place to get becalmed (no wind for the sails).<br>
<br>
 It's just doubly nice that a launch wants to be at the equator <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
 Yet another nice thing about the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.luf.org">Millennial Project</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> book. His ocean floating cities would be natural: open waters far away from others are good spots for floating rectennae (SPS energy to drive laser launchers, water eloctrolysis for fuels, methanation for fuels to export to Earth markets). Laser thermal launchers can use sea-level air to push cargo up, aeroentry barges of asteroidal materials can be splash-landed at sea and towed to ports for sale.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://oceania.org/mall/millimag.html"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://oceania.org/images/plate2s.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;This composite satellite image shows concentrations of planetary biomass. On land, forests and grasslands are indicated in green; at sea, plankton are shown in yellow and red. The areas of highest oceanic productivity are concentrated along coastlines and in regions of upwelling. Mid-ocean zones are nearly devoid of algae and most other life. These vast oceanic deserts, indicated in dark blue and purple, can be colonized without disturbing any preexisting ecologies.&quot;<br>
